data.content:
## .NET 8 Migration: `TimedExecutor`

### Key Breaking Changes

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 | Impact |
|---|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** | Hard crash |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** | Hard crash |
| `ThreadAbortException` | Never raised | Dead code |

`Thread.Abort()` was removed because it corrupts application state — it can interrupt code mid-execution inside `finally` blocks, locks, and static constructors.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    /// <summary>
    /// Executes work with a timeout using cooperative cancellation.
    /// The work delegate must observe the CancellationToken to be
    /// truly cancellable; otherwise the timeout only abandons the wait.
    /// </summary>
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(
        Func<CancellationToken, T> work,
        TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Block the caller, just like the original Thread.Join(timeout) did.
            task.Wait(cts.Token);
            return task.Result;
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            // Unwrap single-exception aggregates to match original behavior.
            throw new AggregateException(ex.InnerException!);
        }
    }

    /// <summary>
    /// Drop-in overload for legacy callers that don't support cancellation.
    /// The token is silently discarded — timeout only abandons the wait,
    /// the work continues running in the background until it finishes.
    /// </summary>
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        return ExecuteWithTimeout(ct => work(), timeout);
    }
}
```

### Critical Pitfalls

**1. Cooperative cancellation is not forced termination.**
The old `Thread.Abort()` killed work mid-flight. The new model *requests* cancellation — the work must check the token:

```csharp
// BAD — will never actually cancel
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(ct =>
{
    while (true) { /* infinite loop ignoring ct */ }
    return 42;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));

// GOOD — checks the token
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(ct =>
{
    while (!ct.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
        DoChunkOfWork();
    }
    return 42;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
```

**2. Fire-and-forget leak with the legacy overload.**
The `Func<T>` overload (no token) throws `TimeoutException` to the caller, but the work keeps running on the thread pool. If the work holds resources (DB connections, file handles), they won't be released until it finishes naturally. Audit all call sites.

**3. Async alternative — prefer this if callers can be async:**

```csharp
public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
    Func<CancellationToken, Task<T>> work,
    TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    try
    {
        return await work(cts.Token).WaitAsync(cts.Token);
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}
```

### Migration Checklist

- Replace all `Thread.Abort` / `ResetAbort` — they throw at runtime
- Update `Func<T>` signatures to `Func<CancellationToken, T>` at call sites
- Pass `CancellationToken` through to I/O APIs (`HttpClient`, `DbCommand`, `Stream`, etc.)
- Remove `catch (ThreadAbortException)` blocks — dead code in .NET 8
- Watch for `Thread.Sleep()` — replace with `Task.Delay(ms, ct)` in async paths
